import{_ as e,o as t,c as i,e as n}from"./app.b0f11a02.js";const r={},s=n('<h2 id="product-management" tabindex="-1"><a class="header-anchor" href="#product-management" aria-hidden="true">#</a> Product Management</h2> <p>Product managers can set the tone early in a project&#39;s lifecycle, ensuring the team knows their responsibilities and accountability to building accessible products.</p> <ol><li>Be aware of <strong>each role&#39;s</strong> high-level accessibility principles.</li> <li>Ensure each role on your team is aware of these principles and keep them in mind from the start: <a href="#content">Content</a>, <a href="#design">Design</a>, and <a href="#engineering">Engineering</a>.</li> <li>Build <strong>accessibility into project workflows</strong> every step of the way, rather than as a retrofit exercise.</li> <li>Learn <strong>Accessibility basics</strong> to understand what makes your team empowered to deliver accessible products and services.</li> <li>Understand the <strong>diversity of users</strong> to better consider how anyone can get the most out of your product.</li> <li>Consult an <strong>accessibility subject matter expert</strong> to review.</li></ol> <h2 id="content" tabindex="-1"><a class="header-anchor" href="#content" aria-hidden="true">#</a> Content</h2> <p>Writing accessibly ensures your content is easier for everyone to read.</p> <ol><li><strong>Plain Language.</strong> Can you quickly understand the main points of the content?</li> <li><strong>Scannability.</strong> Can you scan the page without significantly pausing through long passages?</li> <li><strong>Images.</strong> Do your images have descriptive alt text?</li> <li><strong>Links.</strong> Do link sufficiently describe its destination?</li> <li><strong>Information Architecture.</strong> Are the application\u2019s parts organized such that any can navigate easily?</li></ol> <h2 id="design" tabindex="-1"><a class="header-anchor" href="#design" aria-hidden="true">#</a> Design</h2> <p>Accessibility is usability for everyone, regardless of ability, situation, or circumstance. Treat accessibility as a core principle of Product Design.</p> <ol><li>Adopt a mentality of <strong>Inclusive Design</strong>.</li> <li>Is there sufficient <strong>contrast</strong> between foreground and background content?</li> <li>Is textual information <strong>easy to read and parse</strong>?</li> <li>Are <strong>navigation shortcuts</strong> available for keyboard and screen readers to reach key regions?</li> <li>Familiarize yourself with <strong>assistive technologies</strong>. These include screen readers, screen magnification, ergonomic keyboards, or even zoom capabilities in browsers.</li> <li>Do your designs imply a <strong>logical tab order</strong> for those using a keyboard to navigate throughout.</li> <li>Are all interactive elements reachable through the tab key, and reflect a <strong>perceivable focus indicator</strong>?</li> <li>Do your designs reflect a <strong>perceivable focus indicator</strong> for interactive parts?</li> <li>When a view changes significantly, is it clear to the user <strong>where focus has moved to</strong> (independent of a perceived focus order)?</li> <li>Can any user <strong>understand and fill out</strong> forms? Are they as simple as possible and require only what\u2019s needed for task completion?</li> <li>Is imagery easily distinguished as <strong>meaningful content or decorative</strong>?</li> <li>Is <strong>content understandable</strong> for content associated with images and icons?</li> <li>Are <strong>data visualizations</strong> easy to grasp?</li> <li>Are <strong>touch targets</strong> large enough and easy to reach?</li> <li>Can a <strong>screen reader access</strong> all functionality and content?</li></ol> <h2 id="engineering" tabindex="-1"><a class="header-anchor" href="#engineering" aria-hidden="true">#</a> Engineering</h2> <p>Pretty much everything above plus\u2026</p> <ol><li>Do <strong>heading elements</strong> (e.g. <code>&lt;h1&gt;</code> through <code>&lt;h6&gt;</code>) accurately reflect a logical hierarchy of content and features?</li> <li>Are <strong>semantic HTML elements</strong> being used appropriately, and extended where appropriate with ARIA attributes and roles?</li> <li>Does your <strong>automated accessibility testing</strong> tools provide accurate results?</li></ol>',23),a=[s];function o(l,c){return t(),i("div",null,a)}var d=e(r,[["render",o],["__file","principles-by-role.html.vue"]]);export{d as default};
